Marker 185' 0", medium dark gray to dark gray, argillaceous, relatively hard, carbonaceous, micaceous, numerous thin discontinuous lenses of light gray siltstone (about 4%), also several irregular "shreds" of very light olive gray shale (sideritic) giving mottled appearance in part (these constitiute less than 10% in upper 2' and much less in lower part).
claystone (Seatrock) - greenish gray (5G), relatively firm, slightly silty, few small dark gray colored splotches suggesting carbonaceous material, calcareous in part. Bottom of Core #2 - 208' 10".

claystone (Seatrock) - medium greenish gray to medium gray, several slip fractures, relatively firm, non-calcareous, an occasional carbonaceous rootlet (?) noted in upper part, occasional pyritic zone, grades into
claystone - medium gray, much harder than units above, calcareous, much finely crystalline pyrite, several whole half shells of relatively large brachiopods. Bottom of hole.
coal (Herrin No. 6) See file for detailed log of coal

nodular limestone - medium gray, fine grained argillaceous limestone nodules up to 1 1/2" thick in a gray claystone matrix (about 25%) which contains very fine disseminated pyrite crystals, few thick-shelled fossil fragments (brachiopods)

nodular limestone zone - slightly irregular medium gray limestone nodules up to 1" in thickness in siltstone matrix. Nodules are fine grained, very impure (argillaceous) and show a slight tendency to be septarian with thin calcite filled cracks.

shale - dark gray, silty, hard, micaceous, with several half-shells of brachiopods, and with other fossil fragments, shale is essentially noncalcareous except for fossils. Considerable small scattered pyrite grains.

shale - medium gray, fine-grained (except quite silty in upper foot), well laminated, fairly uniform except for 1/2" pyritic lens at 1' 1 1/2" from top, and several very irregular clusters of pyrite crystals up to 1/2" thick in lower foot, which have tendency to be concentrated on bedding planes and which impact some weakness to rock
shale - medium gray, thinly laminated, carbonaceous plant material and pyritized shell fragments abundant, one thin vitrain band near base.

siltstone - medium gray to medium dark gray, argillaceous, relatively hard, upper few inches contains inclusions or thin lenses of dark gray shale. Similar to unit above, siltstone is thinly interlaminated with thin whispy light medium gray siltstone lenses and laminae, bedding is slightly wavy, two 3/8" limestone nodules similar to those at 188' 2" noted 7" from top, much carbonaceous plant material, some pyritized, scattered throughout, an occasional lens or band up to 1/2" is slightly sideritic, becomes finer downward, grades into
siltstone - somewhat similar to unit above limestone nodules, dark gray argillaceous, an occasional small cluster of pyrite crystals

Claystone, medium-dark gray to olive-gray, massive with angular blocky structure, upper 1.5' has pervasive slickensides as well as pyritic coal stringers (roots?); lower part pyritic and crumbly, with rootlets and few slickensides.  Rapid change at base.
Claystone, olive-gray, mottled, calcareous, numerous limestone nodules; more competent than rock above and below.
Claystone, similar to above but strongly calcareous and lacks roots.
Liemstone, olive-gray, argillaceous, nodular, in claystone matrix.
Mudstone, dark olive gray, massive, slickensided, silty, calcareous with a few small limestone nodules.  Expands when wetted.  Lower contact abrupt.

Shale, dark gray (darker downward), silty throughout, micaceous, carbonaceous with scattered plant fragments.  Increasingly fissile downward, becoming pyritic near base, with coalified bark/stems in basal 0.3'.
Shale, dark gray, well laminated, upper part silightly silty, the rest is clay-shale.  Many bands of siderite less than 0.1 feet thick.  Basal 0.7' is very pyritic.

Siltstone to silty shale, upper part olive-gray and faintly mottled, lower part medium-dark gray.  Becomes more fissile and clay-rich downward.  Siderite bands and nodules are numerous.  Non-calcareous, no fossils.  Lower contact gradational.

Siltstone, olive-gray; the upper part is coarsest and massive and has a greenish cast.  Downward the rock becomes finer grainedd and distinctly bedded; the lower three feet is mottled.  Upper half is slightly calcareous.  Irregular ndoules of yellowish-brown siderite occur throughout along with an intricate network of fracture-fillings of siderite and calcite.  These are definitely fractures, not roots.  They gradually die out in the lower three feet.  Lower contact gradational.

Claystone, dark olive-gray, partly mottled, calcareous throughout.  Upper two feet incompetent and highly slickensided.  No roots observed.  Lower 2.5 feet is more competent and massive to weakly layered.
Claystone, olive-gray, blocky, highly slickensided, pyritic, non-calcareous.  Core badly crumbled.
Claystone, olive-gray, massive to blocky and slickensided, calcareous; lower one foot contains irregular, brecciated limestone nodules.  Gradational contact:

Dolomite, greenish gray, very argillaceous and silty, thoroughly becciated (pedogenic breccia), fractures filled with clay.  Irregular nodules of light gray limestone, resembling cumulus clouds, are about 1/3 of core.  Irregular contact:
Dolomite, medium to dark olive-gray, very hard and dense, sublithographic.  Thoroughly brecciated (pedogenic), with claystone filling larger fractures.  Lower contact fairly sharp.
Limestone septarian concretion, dark gray, extremely hard, microgranular, and dolomitic, Septarian fractures line with whie calcite.  Sharp contact.

Mudstone, dark gray to nearly black, with mottles and thick, irregular inclined bands of olive-gray.  This rock is weakly fissil and varies from slightly silty claystone to coarse siltstone.  Portions are calcareous.  Upper part is pyritic and has pelletal to vaguley brecciated structure.
Mudstone, mottled greenish gray and dark gray, angular blocky structure, calcareous, silty.  Irregular contact:

Mudstone, mottled olive to greenish and dark gray, hard and calcareous, abundant 1-2 cm calcite nodules.  Brachiopods (whole shells) occur near middle.  Rock has blocky structure and pedogenic breccia throughout.  Gradation near base to weak, mottled claystone.

Shale, dark gray with olive-gray mottling, topmost 0.5' is blocky to weakly fissile, the remainder moderately fissile.  Rock is slightly calcareous throughout, increasingly silty downward.  Bands of sand-sized siderite grains occur in lower two feet.  Several slickensided fractures.  Sharp lower contact:

Siltstone, greenish to olive-gray, faintly mottled, well bedded, slightly calcareous.  The upper portion is partly very fine sandstone, a micaceous lithic arenite; interval becomes finer grained downward.  Siderite is common, especially in lower half of interval, in the form of small nodules, irregular bands, and concretions of sand-sized pellets.  Lower part also has large vertical fractures lined with whtie calcite.  Increasing bands and mottles of dark gray near base; gradational contact:
Springfield Coal, bone coal or carbonaceous shale, thinly laminated, with medial bard of hard olive-gray claystone that resembles flint clay.

Claystone, dark olive-gray, blocky to massive, thoroughly slickensided, upper on foot non-calcareous, the remaineder slightly calcareous.  Uppermost 0.2 feet contains sandy lenses and laminae, sand-sized siderite pellets, and streaks of carbonaceous shale.  Carbonaceous debris is common, but no definite roots.  Lower contact gradational.
Claystone, olive gray, blocky, thoroughly slickensided, pyritic, non-calcareous.  Coaly stringers and plant fragments, probably roots, are present.  Contact sharp or rapid gradation:

Claystone, olive-gray, massive, strongly calcareous.  Downward the rock becomes lighter colored, more competent, and contains larger and more numerous limestone nodules.  Lower contact highly irregular.

Dolomite, medium-dark olive-gray, microgranular to very finely granular, with scattered whole brachiopods.  Upper 0.6 feet highly brecciated, with clay-filled fractures extending downward.  The remainder is faintly nodular and brecciated without clay fillings.  Basal contact sharp and inclined about 20 degrees.

Energy Shale, medium to dark gray and olive-gray, the upper six feet distinctly mottled, with an intersecting polygonal fracture pattern; remainder faintly laminated.  Shale is fissile and slightly silty throughout; there are no siderite nodules.  Gradational contact:

Sandstone, medium-light gray, very fine grained, massive to fainly laminated.  Upper part argillaceous, lower part less so.  Upper one foot contains irregular masses of siderite and a network of fine clay-filled fractures.
Shale, grayish black, weakly fissile, pyritic, carbonaceous.  Springfield Coal position.

Shale, medium-dark to dark-gray, well laminated, silty, carbonaceous, plant debris common.  Flattened lenses of pyrite are present, no siderite.  Basal 01. feet highly carbonaceous shale to bone coal.
Silstone, olive-gray, mottled, weakly bedded, non-calcareous, a few slickensides, lower gradational.

Calcareous siltstone or highly impure limestone, mottled dark olive to brownish gray, massive, thoroughly brecciated, with clay filling vertical fractures throughout.  Several slickensided fractures.  Lower contact sharp.
Claystone, dark olive to brownish gray, blocky, pyruitic, rooted, non-calcareous.  Upper 0.3 feet has irregular horizontal bands of grayish black shale.
Claystone, olive gray, blocky to massive, slickensided, caclareous, lower foot contains many small limestone nodules.  Irregular contact:
Claystone, olive-gray, blocky, thoroughly slickensided, badly crumbled; pyritic, rooted, non-calcareous.  Rapid change to:

Energy Shale: siltstone (top) to silty shale (base), medium olive-gray, mottled, well bedded.  Small irregular masses of siderite and calcite along with intricate network of siderite-filled vertical fractures; some may be roots but most are probably shrinkage cracks.
Silty shale, dark gray, more fissile than above and finely carbonaceous, pyritic.  No siderite.  Coarse matted plant debris in basal 0.3 feet.
Silty shale, medium olive-gray, faintly mottled, well bedded, numerous bands and flattened lenses of siderite in the upper 8 feet.  Lower contact gradational.

Carbonaceous shale (Springfield Coal), alternating layers of olive-gray and black claystone.  The olive layers are hackly and slickensided, black layers laminated; lower 0.1 feet is laminated bone coal.  Sharp contact:
Claysonte, dark olive-gray, blocky and slickensided, no roots observed.  Downward becomes increasingly calcareous, light colored, and slightly more competent.  Sharp contact:
Claystone, dark gray, blocky (angular) and highly slickensided; pyritic and carbonaceous, rooted, non-calcareous.  Core badly crumbled.
Claystone, dark olive to greenish gray, more competent than above.  Slickensides abundant, possible roots.  Lower part has small limestone nodules; gradational contact.
Dolomite, olive gray, microgranular, massive except for vertical and inclined clay-filled fractures that may be roots.

Mudstonef with limestone nodules, medium to dark olive and brownish gray (variable), moderately cometent and calcareous.  Upper two feet has highly irregular blebs and masses of light gray limestone, intergrown with a finely intricate network of siderite-filled fractures.  Lower two feet is weakly layered and the limestone nodules tend to follow bedding. Brachiopods (including chonetides) are common in the lower one foot, with shell hash at the base.  Sharp contact:

Shale, medium-dark to dark gray, silty, less so downward.  Upper five feet has lenses and laminae of light gray siltstone (not rhythmic), and plentiful plant fragments.  Remainder lacks laminae and fossils, except basal 0.3 feet contains coalified stems.

Siltstone/shale interlaminated; siltstone light gray, shale meidum-dark gray and slightly mottled.  Interval coarsens upward.  Lamination is planar to slightly wavy and highly rhythmic, spaced three to five mm apart (wider upward) and bundled; probably neap-spring tidal couplets.  A few nodules.  Lower contact gradational.

Claystone, upper 0.5 feet dark gray, upper 1.2 feet non-calcareous, slickensided.  Remainder is calcareous, becoming more competent downward and having limestone nodules in lower 2 1/2 feet.  Core muddy, no examined in detail.

Herrin Coal, bright banded; "blue band" 0.1' of hard nearly black claystone with coal laminae, its base 1.0' above base of seam.  Pyritic fusain layer 2.3' above base.  Upper two feet has wide vertical fractures lined with calcite.  Cleat has pyrite and calcite throughout.
Shale, dark gray (lighter than above), silty, moderately fissilie; abundant plant fossils plus a specimen of Dundarella.  Coaly at base - sharp contact:

Shale, medium to dark olive and greenish gray, strongly mottled dark gray; silty, competent, slightly calcareous.  Good fissility - splits evenly into layers, no slickensides.  Mottling tneds to be banded parallel to bedding.  Small irregular nodules, masses, and fracture-fillings of limestone are common.  Fine vertical fractures outline polygons on bedding.  Limestone nodules in lower 6-7 feet have septarian fractures, and a few pyrite nodules are present.  Sharp contact:

Shale, very dark gray with slightly lenticular, even bands of brownish gray.  Competent, finely silty, moderately fissile, non-calcareous.  Brownish bands are pyritic and slightly calcareous - they may be phosphatic.  Lower part contains small (less than an inch) calcareous nodules.  Pyritized plant fragments are common.  Missing core (0.3') at contact:
